# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1990-swiss-referendums
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Helvetic Republic over several months in 1798.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Modelled after the French Constitution of the Year III of 1795, the new constitution was approved by voters.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] In some places voting took places in public assemblies, whilst in others the local councils took the decision.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Helvetic Republic on 25 May 1802.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Unlike the constitution approved in 1798, the new constitution, known as the Malmaison constitution, did not provide for any referendums.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Non-voters were assumed to have voted in favour of the new constitution, a measure put in place to prevent its rejection.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] As a result, 72.17% of voters were deemed to be in favour.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in Switzerland in July and August 1848, the first referendum on record in the Swiss Confederation.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] The new constitution was approved by 72.8% of voters and a majority of cantons.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] In order to pass, any amendments to the constitution needed a double majority; a majority of the popular vote and majority of the cantons.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] The decision of each canton was based on the vote in that canton.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] Full cantons counted as one vote, whilst half cantons counted as half.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland between 1 and 27 October 1848.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left emerged as the largest group, winning 79 of the 111 seats in the National Council.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] The 111 members of the National Council were elected from 52 single- and multi-member constituencies.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] In six cantons (Appenzell Innerrhoden, Appenzell Ausserrhoden, Glarus, Nidwalden, Obwalden and Uri), National Council members were elected by the Landsgemeinde.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 26 October 1851.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left remained the largest group in the National Council, winning 78 of the 120 seats.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The elections were held under the Federal law concerning the elections to the National Council, which had been passed on 21 December 1850.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The 120 members of the National Council were elected in 49 single- and multi-member constituencies; there was one seat for every 20,000 citizens, with seats allocated to cantons in proportion to their population.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The 1850 law reduced the number of constituencies from 52, but increased the number of seats from 111; Aargau, Glarus, Lucerne, Neuchâtel, Vaud and Zürich gained one seat each, whilst Bern gained three seats.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The law also set the election date as the last Sunday in October and introduced a three-year term.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The elections were held using a three-round system; candidates had to receive a majority in the first or second round to be elected; if it went to a third round, only a plurality was required.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] Voters could cast as many votes as there were seats in their constituency.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1854-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 29 October 1854.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1854-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left remained the largest group in the National Council, winning 80 of the 120 seats.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1857-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 28 October 1857.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1857-swiss-federal-election] Compulsory voting was introduced in the Canton of Schaffhausen for the elections, with the canton seeing the highest turnout at 86.4% compared to the 46.5% figure nationally.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1990-swiss-referendums] Ten referendums were held in Switzerland in 1990.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1990-swiss-referendums] The first six were held on 1 April on four popular initiatives, a federal resolution on viticulture and an amendment to the federal law on the organisation of the federal judiciary.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1990-swiss-referendums] The last four were held on 23 September on two popular initiatives to phase out nuclear power and to stop the construction of any new nuclear power plants, as well as on a federal resolution on the energy article in the Swiss Federal Constitution and an amendment to the federal law on road traffic.
[src:1990-swiss-referendums/1990-swiss-referendums] Whilst the nuclear power phase-out was rejected, the other three proposals were approved.
